							<span class="basher" style="font-size:36px">Wen Nance</span><br />
								<span	style="font-size:18px; font-style:italic">CEO and Head Honcho</span><br />
								<p>
								Paul Rego manages Trinity&rsquo;s intellectual property and technology development.  Working with the executive committee and our IT / web development personnel, Paul leads the company&rsquo;s technology development initiatives focused on providing our customers with the best tools available in the apparel industry for order entry and sales management.
								</p><p>
								Paul lead the development and launch of Trinity&rsquo;s revolutionary Dynamic Image Merchandising system <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">iDesign STUDIO</span>.  In addition to the continual development of STUDIO, Paul is responsible for leading the ongoing improvement of the company&rsquo;s industry-leading order entry system <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">iDesign WORKFLO</span>.
								</p>
								<p>
								Paul&rsquo;s experience in men&rsquo;s apparel began in 1988 in Toronto, Canada where we worked for <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">Harry Rosen</span>, Canada&rsquo;s luxury men&rsquo;s wear chain.  In 1991 he joined the family&rsquo;s upscale custom clothing boutique <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">REGO Bespoke Clothiers</span> located next to the Toronto Stock Exchange.  In 2002, Paul and his father formed <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">Sartorial Instruments &amp; Technology</span> to launch their invention <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">The Fitter</span>; a measuring device and online software application designed to help retailers obtain professional results selling custom apparel.
								</p><p>
								In 2005, Paul realized the family was better at retailing than attempting to help other retailers, and departed the family business to work at <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">Coppley Apparel Group</span>.  Paul&rsquo;s role was to train the company&rsquo;s sales force and retail customers on fitting and measuring best practices.  In 2009 Paul decided to move to the United States to launch a custom shirt line <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">TOUCH</span>, which was recently sold to <span style="font-weight:bold; font-style:italic">Ballin</span>.  Paul joined Trinity Apparel Group in 2011.  
								He now resides in Jacksonville, FL with his wife Nathalie and their 4 cats.  When he&rsquo;s not trying to figure out how Trinity can continue to revolutionize the custom apparel sales experience, he enjoys the sunshine while playing at Florida&rsquo;s numerous golf courses.
